iI purchased an old HP workstation to use as a NAS and router at my		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihome. This
post is a short note of my process of setting it up.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iHardware Choice		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iFor a NAS, you usually have these hardware choices:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Ready-to-use NAS (e.g. Synology)		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros: ready to use out of the box.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Expensive, to the extent of "free hardware for software purchase".		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Harder to customize, when comparing the stock operating system		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwith
various Linux distributions.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Second-hand servers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cheap. Most servers are thrown away by datacenters once their		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwarranty
ends, and are obtained at minimum cost, refurbished and then		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iresold.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Stable. These servers are built to last, and are used in a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idatacenter with
controlled temperature, humidity and no dust.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons：		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Noise. In order to lower the fan speed, you need to modify		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isystem
settings, replace with quieter fans, and/or install a separate		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ifan speed
controller.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Large (mainly concerning rack-mount servers).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Proprietary parts. Server manufacturers customize their components		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ionly
for specific models. You will need to purchase these parts at		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iextra cost
if you want to extend your system.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Second-hand workstations		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cheap and stable, just like second-hand servers.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Lower noise. After all, workstations are meant to be used near		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ioffice
desktops rather than datacenters.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Proprietary parts, same as second-hand servers.\		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- DIY from regular PC parts		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Pros:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Customize to your exact need.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Cons:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Worse performance-to-price ratio compared to second-hand servers		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iand
workstations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Stability of customer-facing parts may be worse than		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ibusiness-facing
servers and workstations.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iAnd I have these requirements for my NAS:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- I want to use Jellyfin video transcoding, H265 if possible. This		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
irequires a
6th gen (Skylake) or newer Intel CPU with integrated		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
igraphics, or an NVIDIA
graphics card.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Other than that, I don't have any needs on performance (except very		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ilow power
CPUs like Intel Atom series).		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Low noise. I'm currently living in a studio apartment, and the NAS		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwill be in
the same room where I sleep.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- I don't like ready-to-use NAS operating systems. I want to install		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iNixOS and
customize it.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- As cheap as it can get.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iBased on the requirements above, I chose to purchase a second-hand		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iworkstation.
Since I'm in the United States at the moment, I purchased		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ia refurbushed HP
workstation on eBay for $50. It's key specifications		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iare:		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Model: HP Z220 SFF		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- CPU: Intel E3-1225 v2		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- RAM: 4GB DDR3		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- HDD: 250GB Spinning Disk		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- PSU: 240W		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- Three PCI-E slots, one x16, one x4, and one x1.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i- One PCI slot.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
