iStorage		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThe first thing to consider for a NAS is data storage.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iThis workstation has 4 SATA ports, two 3.5 inch HDD slots, and one 5		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iinch DVD
drive slot (with a DVD drive in it). I removed the original		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ihard drive, and
installed two brand new 16TB drives as data storage. I		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iplan to set them up in a
RAID-1 array first, and then expand to RAID-5		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iwith an extra drive when I run out
of capacity. ZFS doesn't support		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iconversion from RAID-1 to RAID-5, and ZFS's
kernel module often fails		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ion kernel upgrades due to its out-of-mainline status.
Btrfs, on the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iother hand, has major stability issues with its RAID-5 feature,
and		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icould easily cause a data loss. Therefore, I ended up with Btrfs +		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iLVM
RAID-1, and chose the more flexible LVM for the RAID layer.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iI also installed a 180GB Intel 520 SSD as the boot drive. Although		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iit's an old
drive, it only costs $15, almost as cheap as it gets for		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iSSDs on eBay. In
addition, it uses MLC NANDs which last longer than		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
icurrent TLC NANDs. This drive
will only hold NixOS's system files (in		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i`/nix`), and some configuration files
that are backed up to cloud		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
istorage everyday. Therefore, I'm not worried of data
loss of this		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
idrive.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iIn addition, I set up		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
hBees	URL:https://github.com/Zygo/bees	{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ito deduplicate data
on Btrfs. After RAID-1 of my two drives, I have a		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iusable storage space of
approximately 14.6TB. To effectly deduplicate		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ithem, Bees needs 2GB RAM to create
a hash table of data on drive. With		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
isome additional services running, I quickly
ran out of memory with the		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
ioriginal 4GB RAM. Therefore, I spent an additional
$40 on 16GB of DDR3		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
iECC-UDIMM RAM sticks.		{{server_host}}	{{server_port}}
